http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Visual Art Curriculum Standards for grades 9-12.
Media, Techniques and Processes - Students will understand and apply media, techniques, and processes.
Demonstrate the use of knowledge and technical skills in at least one specific medium.
Demonstrate an understanding of the safe and responsible use of art media and tools.
Create visual art that communicates ideas through the use of media, techniques, and processes.
Analyze, synthesize, and evaluate the application of media, techniques, and processes used to solve visual art problems.
Structures and Functions - Students will use knowledge of both structures and functions.
Demonstrate an understanding of the elements of art and the principles of design.
Critique organizational components (structures) and expressive qualities (functions) of a work of art.
Evaluate the function of a work of art as to utilitarian or intrinsic purposes.
Apply problem-solving skills to create solutions to a specific visual art task.
Evaluation - Students will choose and evaluate a range of subject matter, symbols, and ideas.
Demonstrate an understanding of symbols and their origins.
Evaluate subject matter that reflects personal experiences and environments.
Analyze selected ideas in a work of art.
Research and create a series of related work using a range of subject matter, symbols, and/or ideas.
Historical and Cultural Relationships - Students will understand the visual arts in relation to history and cultures.
Demonstrate an understanding of how historical and contemporary works of art reflect and influence societies and cultures.
Describe the function and explore the meaning of specific art objects within varied cultures, times, and places.
Investigate how history and culture have and will influence the production of art.
Reflecting and Assessing - Students will reflect upon and assess the characteristics and merits of their work and the work of others.
Reflect on the characteristics and merits of their work and the work of others.
Evaluate artworks in order to understand various interpretations.
Assess artworks and their meanings by using a variety of criteria and techniques.
Interdisciplinary Connections - Students will make connections between visual arts and other disciplines.
Examine the correlation of materials, technologies, processes, and terminology used in visual art with those used in other disciplines.
Integrate ideas, issues, and themes in the visual arts and other disciplines.
